In article &lt;1990Apr5.171053.14081@terminator.cc.umich.edu&gt; bryan@terminator.cc.umich.edu (Bryan Beecher) writes:
&gt;
&gt;How does one convince an organization that their part of in-addr.arpa
&gt;is set-up incorrectly and that they need to do something about it?

How about adopting a policy similar to what we taken at uunet.  We refuse
to allow FTP access by any site that doesn't have it's reverse servers
configured.  We find that this usually has enough impact to make the site
set things up right.

I'd love to setup more "passive enforcement" things, although I'd really
like them to cause less mail to be generated to my mailbox.

&gt;On a different subject, would it be a good idea to come up with a
&gt;list of "Things to do when registering a domain"?

Definitely.  I get tired of telling folks what they need to do.  I
have a few "form letters" I send out on the more pertinent things
concerning uunet access, but I'd love to just tell them to read a
guide.

&gt;Any other thoughts about is such a guide is a good idea or what
&gt;might be placed in it?

I'm (slowly) putting together a version of a similar guide for
registering uucp sites in the DNS.  Since I handle an incredible
number of these each month and the admins at such sites often are
*totally* in the dark this is already in high demand.

While I don't think the majority of this guide would be of use for
pure internet folks, it would make a handy set.

